def preprocess_text(text_data):
    preprocessed_text = []
    
    for sentence in tqdm(text_data):
        sentence = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', sentence)
        preprocessed_text.append(' '.join(token.lower()
                                  for token in str(sentence).split()
                                  if token not in stopwords.words('english')))

    return preprocessed_text

from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer


def get_top_n_words(corpus, n=None):
    vec = CountVectorizer().fit(corpus)
    bag_of_words = vec.transform(corpus)
    sum_words = bag_of_words.sum(axis=0)
    words_freq = [(word, sum_words[0, idx])
                  for word, idx in vec.vocabulary_.items()]
    words_freq = sorted(words_freq, key=lambda x: x[1],
                        reverse=True)
    return words_freq[:n]


common_words = get_top_n_words(data['text'], 20)
df1 = pd.DataFrame(common_words, columns=['Review', 'count'])

df1.groupby('Review').sum()['count'].sort_values(ascending=False).plot(
    kind='bar',
    figsize=(10, 6),
    xlabel="Top Words",
    ylabel="Count",
    title="Bar Chart of Top Words Frequency"
)

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

# 1. Initialize the Vectorizer
# Fit the vectorizer ONLY on the training data (x_train) to prevent data leakage.
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
x_train_vectorized = vectorizer.fit_transform(x_train)

# 2. Transform the test data using the *fitted* vectorizer
x_test_vectorized = vectorizer.transform(x_test) # Assuming you have x_test

# 3. Fit the model using the NUMERICAL data
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(x_train_vectorized, y_train)

# 4. Test the model using the NUMERICAL data
print(accuracy_score(y_train, model.predict(x_train_vectorized)))
